              "headline": "Jameela Jamil Sparks Conversations on Mental Health, Inclusivity and Feminism",
              "introtext": "Actor, writer and activist Jameela Jamil's new podcast series is a voice of change. Read her exclusive chat with Bazaar India.",
              "fulltext": "&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;Jameela Jamil has launched her Instagram account @i_weigh with a simple message&amp;mdash;self-love. It seemed a radical act, to encourage truly embracing yourself, in a world where people are constantly shamed for their body type, colour, or sexuality, especially online. Two years since it began, it has become a safe space for over a million followers, who applaud and empower one another through posts that celebrate who they are&amp;mdash;beyond the number on their weighing scale. This April, Jamil amplified the movement through the launch of her podcast series.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt='image--0042_112320042755.jpg' src='https://akm-img-a-in.tosshub.com/sites/gloss99/resources/embed/202011/image--0042_112320042755.jpg' title='image--0042_112320042755.jpg' /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Harper&amp;rsquo;s Bazaar:&lt;/strong&gt; What have you learned about dealing with shaming culture?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jameela Jamil:&lt;/strong&gt; That shame is rarely something we develop ourselves. We ingest it from the outside and harbour it as if it is our truth. Identifying its origin is the first step towards dismantling it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HB:&lt;/strong&gt; From Tarana Burke and Gloria Steinem to Russel Brand and Neal Brennan&amp;mdash;how did you choose your guest line-up?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;JJ:&lt;/strong&gt; I&amp;rsquo;m looking for honesty and humour. The episodes deal with hard subjects, and a dose of funny helps! I&amp;rsquo;ve invited guests with interesting journeys, who don&amp;rsquo;t make the rest of us feel alone in ours&amp;mdash;people I admire, and whom I can learn from.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt='image--0032_112320042837.jpg' src='https://akm-img-a-in.tosshub.com/sites/gloss99/resources/embed/202011/image--0032_112320042837.jpg' title='image--0032_112320042837.jpg' /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HB:&lt;/strong&gt; What drives you to be so outspoken on social media, even when you often receive so much criticism from it?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;JJ:&lt;/strong&gt; I don&amp;rsquo;t see activism or life as a popularity contest. I think it&amp;rsquo;s important that I don&amp;rsquo;t get used as an example of an outspoken woman chased into the shadows. That&amp;rsquo;s what they want when they publicly shame me&amp;mdash;to send a warning flare to other women inspired to speak out. But I will never, ever shut up. I will make my mistakes, I will have my lessons, I will grow, I will laugh, and I will thrive.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HB:&lt;/strong&gt; What are your favourite podcasts?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;JJ&lt;/strong&gt;:I think Russell Brand is brilliant, but I haven&amp;rsquo;t really investigated many others. When I started mine, I felt like I was in the unknown! I hope it keeps people company and makes them feel seen, and that they learn alongside me. I Weigh with Jameela Jamil is now streaming on Stitcher, Apple Podcasts, and Spotify.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;",
